b'id":"MDExOlB1bGxSZXF1ZXN0NTY5MDcxMzEx","number":39660,"title":"CLN: Styler Types for CSS variables on `ctx` object. ","user":{"l'
b'as/pull/39660.patch"},"body":"- [ ] tests changed / passed\\r\\n- [ ] Ensure all linting tests pass, see [here](https://pandas.pyd'
b'ata.org/pandas-docs/dev/development/contributing.html#code-standards) for how to run them\\r\\n- [ ] whatsnew entry\\r\\n\\r\\n`Styler'
b"` currently has three formats for keeping track of CSS:\\r\\n\\r\\n A) `CSSList type: [('a1', 'v1'), ('a2', 'v2')]`\\r\\n B) `List[str"
b"] type: ['a1:v1', 'a2:v2']`\\r\\n C) `Str type: 'a1:v1; a2:v2;'`\\r\\n\\r\\n`C` is only ever used as user input format, and now, as of"
b' #39564 `C` can be used in *all* cases for user input (albeit `A` remains available for backwards compatibility in `.set_table_s'
b'tyles()`)\\r\\n\\r\\n`A` remains the most algorithimcally accessible, and is what `C` is already converted to in some cases for inte'
b'rnal variables.\\r\\n\\r\\n`B` is only ever used by one internal variable. The `ctx` object is updated with `B` type converted from '
b'`C`. For final render this `B` type is converted to `A` type for looping. In the process, white space is poorly handled.\\r\\n\\r\\n'
b'This PR eliminates `B` type and converts `C` directly to `A`. \\r\\n\\r\\nTests using the `ctx` object needed updating for new type.'

b'"active_lock_reason":null,"body":"#### Is your feature request related to a problem?\\r\\n\\r\\nYes. Often I have 2 columns: start a'

b"ed mostly int64 and for this is it is a bit slow.\\r\\n\\r\\n#### Describe the solution you'd like\\r\\n\\r\\nSeries.explode_range metho"
b'd\\r\\n\\r\\n```\\r\\ndef explode_range(\\r\\n    self, stop, left_shift=0, right_shift=0, ignore_index: bool = False\\r\\n) -> \\"Series\\"'
b':\\r\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\r\\n    Creates series from exploded ranges from this series to the ones given in stop\\r\\n\\r\\n    Currently works'
b' only in int64\\r\\n    left_shift and right_shift parameters are used to delay or hasten start - stop\\r\\n\\r\\n    .. versionadded:'
b': 1.2.x\\r\\n\\r\\n    Parameters\\r\\n    ----------\\r\\n    stop: Series providing stop point\\r\\n    left_shift: shift for start poin'
b't - 0 includes it, 1 not\\r\\n    right_shift: shift for end point - 0 excludes it, 1 includes\\r\\n    ignore_index : bool, default'
b' False\\r\\n        If True, the resulting index will be labeled 0, 1, \xe2\x80\xa6, n - 1.\\r\\n\\r\\n    Returns\\r\\n    -------\\r\\n    Series'
b'\\r\\n        Exploded ranges to rows; index will be duplicated for these rows.\\r\\n```\\r\\n\\r\\n#### API breaking implications\\r\\n\\r'

b'nts `concat` for DataFrames using the ArrayManager, and all tests in `pandas/tests/reshape/` already pass. \\r\\n\\r\\nSummary of th'
b'e changes:\\r\\n\\r\\n* In `internals/concat.py`, I added a `concatenate_block_managers` equivalent for ArrayManagers. This function'
b' rather simply reindexes the managers and then concats the arrays (axis=0) or combines them in a single manager (axis=1).\\r\\n* T'
b'he main problem with that simple approach is that when reindexing the ArrayManager with the given indexer, we do not yet know th'
b'e resulting dtype for when a new all-NA column needs to be added (i.e. the common dtype we would find when actually concatting).'
b" And we can't make this eg an all-NaN object array, as that would influence the `find_common_type` logic.\\r\\n* The way I tried t"
b'o solve this at the moment is by adding a dummy \\"proxy\\" object to signal such an all-NA array (the `NullArrayProxy` class), on'
b'ly tracking its length. And when actually concatting, we can replace this with an actual all-NA array after we determined the re'
b'sulting dtype. This proxy object only lives inside the concatting code (it only gets created when we will call `concat_compat` a'
b'nd inside this function they always get replaced), so the user will never see this. \\r\\n* An alternative could be to first deter'
b'mine what the resulting dtype will be in `internals/concat.py` so we can pass this to the `reindex` functionality, and after rei'
b'ndexing do the actual concatenation. But IMO that will be more complex; the concat / find_common_type logic gets involved twice '
b'(before and after reindexing), and getting those dtypes for which we want to know the common type is also quite tricky before ac'
b'tually reindexing the manager. \\r\\n\\r\\nBasically, this replaces the 600 lines of code of `internals/concat.py` with 25 lines of '
b'`concatenate_array_managers` + the `NullArrayProxy` and `_array_from_proxy` code in `dtypes/concat.py` (but I am quite likely st'
b'ill missing some corner cases!)\\r\\n\\r\\nNote: I did not explicitly test `copy=True/False` behaviour for concat along the columns '
